<subSubSection box="[1066,1202,1841,1868]" pageId="40" pageNumber="721" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="40.[1003,1266,1810,1868]" box="[1066,1202,1841,1868]" pageId="40" pageNumber="721">
(
<figureCitation box="[1075,1151,1841,1868]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="41.[132,143,1917,1934]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@41.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIG. 28. — Theropod teeth from Angeac-Charente: A-C, Archaeopterygid tooth (ANG M-09) in lingual (A) and labial (B, C) views; D, Archaeopterygid tooth (ANG M-08) in lingual view; E, F, cf. Nuthetes sp. (ANG M-45) in lingual (E) and distal (F) views; G, cf. Nuthetes sp. (ANG M-61) in lingual view; H, tooth of Tyrannosauroidea indet. (ANG17-5342) in lingual view; I, J, tooth of Tyrannosauroidea indet. (ANG M-73) in lingual (I) and distal (J) views; K, Megalosauridae? indet. (ANG17 R-1748) in lingual view (J); L, M, Megalosauridae? indet. (ANG17-5650) in labial (L) and (M) lingual views; N, Megalosauridae? indet. (ANG M-121) in lingual view. Scale bar: A, B, 1 mm; C-F, 400 µm; G, 5 mm; H-N, 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902103" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902103/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="721">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
H-J)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="42" lastPageNumber="723" pageId="40" pageNumber="721" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="40.[812,1455,1906,2028]" box="[813,952,1906,1932]" pageId="40" pageNumber="721">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="40.[812,1455,1906,2028]" lastBlockId="42.[813,1457,1905,2028]" lastPageId="42" lastPageNumber="723" pageId="40" pageNumber="721">
There are at least eight teeth with a very characteristic morphology. They are D-shaped in cross-section with the mesial carina lingually displaced (
<figureCitation box="[1097,1172,2001,2027]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="41.[132,143,1917,1934]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@41.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIG. 28. — Theropod teeth from Angeac-Charente: A-C, Archaeopterygid tooth (ANG M-09) in lingual (A) and labial (B, C) views; D, Archaeopterygid tooth (ANG M-08) in lingual view; E, F, cf. Nuthetes sp. (ANG M-45) in lingual (E) and distal (F) views; G, cf. Nuthetes sp. (ANG M-61) in lingual view; H, tooth of Tyrannosauroidea indet. (ANG17-5342) in lingual view; I, J, tooth of Tyrannosauroidea indet. (ANG M-73) in lingual (I) and distal (J) views; K, Megalosauridae? indet. (ANG17 R-1748) in lingual view (J); L, M, Megalosauridae? indet. (ANG17-5650) in labial (L) and (M) lingual views; N, Megalosauridae? indet. (ANG M-121) in lingual view. Scale bar: A, B, 1 mm; C-F, 400 µm; G, 5 mm; H-N, 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902103" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902103/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="721">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
H-J). The mesial margin is only slightly convex. The distal carina is denticulate along its entire length, while the mesial carina is only denticulate on its apical quarter.The denticles extend over the apex. There are 12-13 denticles per 
<quantity box="[392,458,2001,2028]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="42" pageNumber="723" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
on mesial and distal carinae. Two longitudinal grooves are present on the lingual side of ANG M-73, below the denticulate mesial carina (
<figureCitation box="[1353,1441,1937,1964]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="41.[132,143,1917,1934]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@41.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIG. 28. — Theropod teeth from Angeac-Charente: A-C, Archaeopterygid tooth (ANG M-09) in lingual (A) and labial (B, C) views; D, Archaeopterygid tooth (ANG M-08) in lingual view; E, F, cf. Nuthetes sp. (ANG M-45) in lingual (E) and distal (F) views; G, cf. Nuthetes sp. (ANG M-61) in lingual view; H, tooth of Tyrannosauroidea indet. (ANG17-5342) in lingual view; I, J, tooth of Tyrannosauroidea indet. (ANG M-73) in lingual (I) and distal (J) views; K, Megalosauridae? indet. (ANG17 R-1748) in lingual view (J); L, M, Megalosauridae? indet. (ANG17-5650) in labial (L) and (M) lingual views; N, Megalosauridae? indet. (ANG M-121) in lingual view. Scale bar: A, B, 1 mm; C-F, 400 µm; G, 5 mm; H-N, 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902103" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902103/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="723">Fig. 28I</figureCitation>
). When preserved, the enamel texture is irregular (
<bibRefCitation author="Hendrickx" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hendrickx" pageId="42" pageNumber="723" pagination="982797" refId="ref41131" refString="HENDRICKX C., MATEUS O. &amp; ARAUJO R. 2015 a. - A proposed terminology of theropod teeth (Dinosauria, Saurischia). Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology 35: e 982797. https: // doi. org / 10.108 0 / 02724634.2015.982797." type="journal article" year="2015" yearSuffix="a">
Hendrickx 
<emphasis box="[813,864,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="723">et al.</emphasis>
2015a
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
