<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="724" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="43.[131,774,215,433]" pageId="43" pageNumber="724">
The morphology of these teeth and in particular the lingual offset of the mesial carina are typical of tyrannosauroids (
<bibRefCitation author="Holtz" box="[142,274,279,305]" firstAuthor="Holtz" pageId="43" pageNumber="724" pagination="111 - 136" refId="ref41337" refString="HOLTZ T. R. 2004. - Tyrannosauroidea, in WEISHAMPEL D. B., DODSON P. &amp; OSMOLSKA H. (eds), The Dinosauria. University of California Press, Berkeley: 111 - 136." type="book chapter" year="2004">Holtz 2004</bibRefCitation>
). They are very similar to that described in the Bathonian 
<taxonomicName authority="von Huene, 1926" authorityName="von Huene" authorityYear="1926" baseAuthorityName="Woodward" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[300,559,311,337]" class="Reptilia" family="Megalosauridae" genus="Proceratosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Saurischia" pageId="43" pageNumber="724" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bradleyi">
<emphasis box="[300,559,311,337]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="724">Proceratosaurus bradleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the Barremian 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Hutt, Naish, Martill, Barker &amp; Newbery" authorityYear="2001" box="[133,255,344,369]" class="Reptilia" family="Not" genus="Eotyrannus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="43" pageNumber="724" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[133,255,344,369]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="724">Eotyrannus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hutt" box="[274,463,343,369]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hutt" pageId="43" pageNumber="724" pagination="227 - 242" refId="ref41533" refString="HUTT S., NAISH D., MARTILL D. M., BARKER M. J. &amp; NEWBERRY P. 2001. - A preliminary account of a new tyrannosauroid theropod from the Wessex Formation (Early Cretaceous) of southern England. Cretaceous Research 22: 227 - 242. https: // doi. org / 10.1006 / cres. 2001.0252" type="journal article" year="2001">
Hutt 
<emphasis box="[339,396,343,369]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="724">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="RAUHUT O. W. M. &amp; MILNER A. C. &amp; MOORE- FAY S. C." box="[481,700,343,369]" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="43" pageNumber="724" pagination="155 - 195" part="158" refId="ref47513" refString="RAUHUT O. W. M., MILNER A. C. &amp; MOORE- FAY S. C. 2010. - Cranial osteology and phylogenetic position of the theropod dinosaur Proceratosaurus bradleyi (Woodward, 1910) from the Middle Jurassic of England. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 158: 155 - 195. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2009.00591. x" title="Cranial osteology and phylogenetic position of the theropod dinosaur Proceratosaurus bradleyi (Woodward, 1910) from the Middle Jurassic of England" type="journal article" year="2010">
Rauhut 
<emphasis box="[576,632,343,369]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="724">et al.</emphasis>
2010
</bibRefCitation>
). This discovery confirms the presence of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[539,742,375,401]" pageId="43" pageNumber="721" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Tyrannosauroidea">Tyrannosauroidea</taxonomicName>
in Europe at the beginning of the Early Cretaceous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
